threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a MIPS-based botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (BASHLITE) or Mirai families. It exhibits classic malware behaviors: daemonization via fork and setsid, string obfuscation using XOR-based decryption (sub_411efc/sub_411fe0), and process-killing logic intended to eliminate competing malware (sub_40f228). The sample contains multiple large functions (e.g., sub_408b28, sub_400e20, sub_40a880) dedicated to crafting raw network packets for DDoS attacks, including TCP and UDP flooding with randomized header values. It also features a remote shell execution capability (/bin/sh) and attempts to resolve C2 addresses from a list of obfuscated strings.
